TY  - JOUR
T1  - Determining Legislative Preferences on the Minimum Wage: An Economic Approach
AU  - Silberman, Jonathan I.
AU  - Durden, Garey C.
Y1  - 1976/04/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260434
DO  - 10.1086/260434
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 317
EP  - 329
VL  - 84
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper utilizes an economic model to analyze the determinants of legislative decision making. The model is empirically tested using the statistical technique of n-chotomous multivariate probit analysis. The legislative issue addressed is the 1973 amendment to the Fair Labor Standards Act. The amendment proposed to increase the minimum wage and the number of workers covered. The dependent variable denotes a representative's voting pattern on the minimum wage; the independent variables represent economic characteristics of a legislator's congressional district. The hypothesized linkages between the set of independent variables and legislative voting patterns were generally substantiated in the empirical tests.
AB  - This paper utilizes an economic model to analyze the determinants of legislative decision making. The model is empirically tested using the statistical technique of n-chotomous multivariate probit analysis. The legislative issue addressed is the 1973 amendment to the Fair Labor Standards Act. The amendment proposed to increase the minimum wage and the number of workers covered. The dependent variable denotes a representative's voting pattern on the minimum wage; the independent variables represent economic characteristics of a legislator's congressional district. The hypothesized linkages between the set of independent variables and legislative voting patterns were generally substantiated in the empirical tests.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260434
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260434
Y2  - 2024/03/22
